 time (prior to the release of {{game|Black and White|s|Pokémon Black 2 and White 2|2}}).\n\n===Origin===\nZorua is likely based on the \'\'{{wp|kitsune}}\'\' of Japanese folklore, a mythical {{wp|fox}} capable of shape-shifting. The concept of a Zorua still having its tail while in human form refers to how a \'\'kitsune\'\' has difficulty in hiding its tail when it takes on human form in some stories. Its facial markings draw inspiration from \'\'{{wp|Kabuki}}\'\' and \'\'{{wp|Noh}}\'\' theater makeup.\n\nIn addition, Zorua\'s habit of replacing children with itself is similar to Irish folklore about the {{wp|changeling}}, a fairy-child that replaces human children kidnapped by fairies or, in some tales, the devil. Zorua also resembles the {{wp|trickster}} characters of many cultures in both appearance and behavior; such characters are often depicted as foxes.\n\n====Name origin====\nZorua may be a combination of \'\'zorro\'\' (Spanish for \'\'fox\'\') and \'\'rua\'\' (Irish for \'\'red\'\', possibly referring to its red fur; \'\'madra rua\'\' is Irish for \'\'fox\'\').\n\n==In other languages==\n{{Other languages|type=Dark|type2=Dark\n|ja=ゾロア \'\'Zorua\'\'|jameaning=From \'\'{{tt|zorro|fox in Spanish}}\'\'\n|fr=Zorua|frmeaning=Same as English/Japanese name\n|es=Zorua|esmeaning=Same as English/Japanese name\n|de=Zorua|demeaning=Same as English/Japanese name\n|it=Zorua|itmeaning=Same as English/Japanese name\n|ko=조로아 \'\'Zorua\'\'|komeaning=Transliteration of Japanese name\n|zh_cmn= 索羅亞 / 索罗亚 \'\'Suǒluóyǎ\'\' / \'\'Suǒluóyà\'\'|zh_cmnmeaning=Transliteration of Japanese name\n|ru=Зоруа \'\'Zorua\'\'|rumeaning=Transcription of English name\n}}\n<br clear="left">\n\n==Related articles==\n* [[Zorua (M13)]]\n* [[Luke\'s Zorua]]\n* [[N\'s Zorua]]\n<!--\n==Notes==\n<references />-->\n\n==External links==\n* {{wp|Zorua and Zoroark|Article on Wikipedia}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{PokémonPrevNext/Head|type=Dark}}\n{{PokémonPrevNext/Pokémon|type=Dark|prevnum=569|prev=Garbodor|nextnum=571|ne